Market Study - Food Industry Exports

Openclassrooms, Data Analyst Course
Project 5 - Michael Orange

A company in the food industry specialized in Chicken Meat is looking at expanding worldwide. All countries are considered.

Production is located in France.
The mission is to provide the company with data ensuring it will collaborate with the most promising export market countries.

Grouping countries in 'clusters' based on their similarity is required.
Default variables are:

  • population growth,
  • calory supply per capita
  • protein supply per capita,
  • prevalence of animal proteins in the mix.

Additional relevant variable might be included (ex. GDP per capita)

Section 1 - Import Datasets

Section 2 - Preparation

  • Data overview
  • Transform data (Normalization)

Section 3 - PCA - Principal Component Analysis

  • Number of components
  • Hierarchical Clustering after PCA
  • Synthetic variables
  • Correlation Circles
  • Individuals factor map
  • Centroids

Section 4 - Analysis of the clusters

  • Exportation to high income developped countries
    • Exportation to EU countries facilitated
    • Exportation to non-EU developped countries
  • Exportation to isolated countries with high dependance to importations
  • Final selection: 5 EU countries and 3 non EU countries

Section 5 - Testing Hypothesis

  • Shapiro test
  • Henry Line
  • Comparaison test between clusters

Preparation

Data overview

  • pop_growth = growth of the population (2103-2017)
  • gdp_per_capita_usd = GDP per capita in USD (2017)
  • political_stability_index = Index of the Political Stability and Absence of Violence (2017)
  • food_supply_kcalcapitaday = Food supply in kcal/capita/day (2017)
  • protein_supply_gcapitaday = Protein supply in g /capita/day (2017)
  • protein_animal_over_protein = Food pourcentage of proteins from Animals over the total proteins (2017)
  • growth_protein_animal_gcapitaday = growth of the protein animal per capita (2013-2017)
  • protein_poultry_gcapitaday = protein supply from Poultry in g/capita/day (2017)
  • prod_poultry_over_domsupply = Production Poultry over Domestic Supply Poultry (2017)
  • net_import_poultry_over_domsupply = (Imports - Exports) over Domestic Supply Poultry (2017)
  • growth_net_import_poultry = growth of the net imports of Poultry (2013-2017)
  • growth_domsupply_poultry = growth of the domestic supply of Poultry (2013-2017)

Significant outliers:

  • Population growth higher than 20% : ['Oman']
  • GDP per capita higher than 80 000 : ['Luxembourg']
  • Import of Poultry 300+ % higher than internal consumption : ['China, Hong Kong SAR']
  • Net Import (Import - Export) of Poultry at least 300% lower than domestic supply : ['Netherlands', 'Belgium']
  • 600+ % growth of Poultry Imports : ['Cambodia', 'Turkmenistan']
  • 200+ % gowth of Poulry Domestic Supply : ['Malawi', 'Mozambique']

Analysis of the clusters

The Poultry market is a strong competitive market. The international Poultry market, whose growth is being powered by emerging countries, is focusing on cost rather than quality. Cost is the strategic variable for success on the international poultry markets.

In poultry production, French farms are more numerous and also smaller than the ones from the main producers in Europe and outside (Brazil, USA, Thailand, China). In France, poultry farms have a smaller capacity because of the importance of quality and origin labels (Red Label, organic, Appellation dOrigine Contrle). With farm sizes which dont allow for large economies of scale, and with labour costs above some of its competitors, the French Poultry sector is facing challenges on exports.

With a gourmet image and high quality products, it is recommended for a French Poultry producer to explore export markets with a clientele ready to pay for premium products. Countries with a higher level of development are preferred.

Production is based in France and part of the European Union (UE). Exportation to another EU members is facilitated in terms of regulations, standards and import tariffs.

Exportation to high-income developed countries

Cluster 10 is our cluster of choice witht the best country attributes regarding the level of development, net importations and growth of the local demand for Poultry products.
['Australia', 'Austria', 'Canada', 'Denmark', 'Finland', 'France', 'Germany', 'Iceland', 'Ireland', 'Israel', 'China, Macao SAR', 'New Zealand', 'Norway', 'Sweden', 'Switzerland', 'China, Taiwan Province of', 'United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland', 'United States of America', 'Luxembourg']

The countries in Cluster 10 bordering on France are: Switzerland, Luxembourg, Germany and United Kingdom.

  • Switzerland: There is a decrease of the Poultry imports between 2013-2017. However due to the very close distance from France, their high GDP per capita, and the significant size of their Poultry net importations, Switzerland remains in the selection.
  • Luxembourg: The size of the market is quite limited. However due to the very close distance from France, their belonging to EU, their very high GDP per capita and their strong dependance to Poultry importations (0 local production), Luxembourg remains in the selection.
  • United Kingdom: there is a decrease of their importations (due to an increase of their production). However due to the very close distance from France, their belonging to EU and the important size of their Poultry net importations (first Poultry Market in EU), United Kingdom remains in the selection.
  • Germany: no arbitrage required for Germany. It is a natural choice (matching all criterias) in our selection. See below.

The best export candidates from Cluster 10 are shortlisted with the following attributes:

  • minimum required within EU: net imports > 30 000 tons, growth > 2%, production < 90 % of the local demand
  • minimum required outside EU: net imports > 150 000 tons, growth > 15%, production < 90 % of the local demand

cluster 6 6

EU selection in Cluster 6 ['Czechia']
Outside EU selection in Cluster 6 ['Cuba']

Czechia is not kept in the selection. It is an interesting option to explore due to their belonging to the EU, and the significant growth of the Poultry internal demand (22 % from 2013 to 2017) leading to a significant growth of their imports. However imporations from Poland (a lower-cost Poultry EU Exporter and closer geographically) are a threat due to the Czechia relatively low GDP per capita.

Cuba is not kept in the selection due to a combination of factors:

  • GDP per capita is relatively low which is a challenge for premium products from France.
  • Cuba is geographically closed to the 2 largest Poultry exporters : Brazil and the USA.
  • There is a liquidity and currency risk due to the US sanctions. While China is now the main Cuba's business partner and lender, China is also a major Poultry exporter.
  • US sanctions are unpredictable (US presidents' political agenda) and applicable to French businesses due to extraterritorial US laws.

Note: Japan is the first worldwide market in terms of importations. It has been not included from the selection mainly due to a decline of their internal domestic supply (higher than their population decline) combined with a very strong increase of their Poultry production - +51% - during the same period (2013-2017). While their demand is decreasing, their production capacity is now exceeding 90%. Their production could meet in the future their internal demand.

Final selection: 6 EU countries and 3 non EU countries

Testing Hypothesis

In order to evaluate if the variable follows a normal distribution (gaussian distribution), we measure the difference between the repartition function of a normal distribution and the variable.

  • H0: F = F0 - F0 being a normal distribution
  • H1: F!= F0

                else: 
                    print('group{} vs group {} - same distribution (fail to reject H0) -  statistic: {}, value: {}'.format(k+1, i+1, stat, pvalue))
